Coffee fueled early morning thread:

Lately, for a work thing, I've been doing a bit of research into TTRPGs and board games. I'm finding it fascinating. 

But I'm also growing to despise the 'buy the game, then buy six variably priced expansions for a fuller experience' model.

Admittedly, I'm not 100% on just how 'necessary' this is. But it seems the core game is rather basic in comparison to a fully fleshed out game with all the bolt-on extras. Certain of the additional bits you can buy seem to only add fancy plastic figurines.

A case in point:
Aliens - Another Glorious Day in the Corps.

This is a game that offers players the chance to re-enact the plot of the movie Aliens. IRRESISTIBLE!

Oh wait... to get the full experience and fight the Alien Queen costs another £65? RESISTIBLE. https://t.co/2VaiEJdtKb

@ElessiRin Always best to take some time to regroup and recharge after a blow like this. 

It's all part of bouncing back.

This piques my interest because it's more Horizon Zero Dawn (also, interestingly, there's a narrative aspect that places it after the events of the game.)

Feedback in the online board game community suggests that it's excellently designed, but quite repetitive.

There's a TON of planned expansions, though. Albeit pricey ones. Probably due to the inclusion of some properly massive figurines to depict the game's procession of deadly robot creatures.

Check out this chonker! I don't even LIKE this stuff, but that's impressive. https://t.co/luCQ6mt8Av

Most of the planned expansions for the board game (as far as I can tell, they're not available to buy in the UK yet) take their names from key parts of the game. 'The Heart of the Nora,' for example. Even the Frozen Wilds DLC gets an expansion module named after it.

I really need to look into this more and make sure I understand exactly what's being offered to consumers. 

If any of my followers are into this stuff, I'd love to hear some perspectives. Do you guys feel this is a hard sell, or is it something you're happy to throw money at?

I'm no expert in this stuff, and I have no idea how commonplace this is as a practice in selling modern board games. But it seems like a very cynical sales strategy to me. Almost as if these planned expansions are a tacit admission that the core game isn't... finished?

Moving on, though, I see Horizon Zero Dawn's got its own board game adaptation. And it looks kind of simple at a glance. Like a mash-up of a tabletop war game and a collectable card game. https://t.co/X4Z8n3N1c7
There's a LOT of these in the works. Mostly looking like they add in the robotic creatures from the video game, along with rules to govern how they're implemented.

I dread to think what it'd be like with kids underfoot!
